---
title: Keep a Changelog
description: Don’t let your friends dump git logs into changelogs.
language: en
version: 1.1.0
---
.header
  .title
    %h1= current_page.data.title
    %h2= current_page.data.description

  = link_to data.links.changelog do
    Version
    %strong= current_page.metadata[:page][:version]

  %pre.changelog{ lang: "en" }= File.read("CHANGELOG.md")

.answers
  %h3#what
    %a.anchor{ href: "#what", aria_hidden: "true" }
    What is a changelog?

  %p.updated
    A changelog is a document which contains a curated, chronologically
    ordered list of notable changes for each version of a project.

  %h3#why
    %a.anchor{ href: "#why", aria_hidden: "true" }
    Why keep a changelog?

  %p.updated
    To make it easier for users and contributors to see precisely what
    notable changes have been made between each iteration of the project.

  %h3#who
    %a.anchor{ href: "#who", aria_hidden: "true" }
    Who needs a changelog?

  %p
    People do. Whether consumers or developers, the end users of
    software are human beings who care about what's in the software. When
    the software changes, people want to know why and how.

.good-practices
  %h3#how
    %a.anchor{ href: "#how", aria_hidden: "true" }
    How do I make a good changelog?

  %h4#principles
    %a.anchor{ href: "#principles", aria_hidden: "true" }
    Guiding Principles

  %ul
    %li
      Changelogs are <em>for humans</em>, not machines.
    %li.updated
      Every single version should have an entry.
    %li.updated
      Changes of the same type should be grouped.
    %li.updated
      Direct links to versions and sections should exist.
    %li.updated
      The first version listed should be the latest.
    %li.updated
      Release dates should be listed for each version.
    %li.updated
      Use of #{link_to "versioning schemes", data.links.schemes} should be noted.

  %a.anchor{ href: "#types", aria_hidden: "true" }
  %h4#types Types of changes

  %ul
    %li
      %code Added
      for new features.
    %li
      %code Changed
      for changes in existing functionality.
    %li
      %code Deprecated
      for soon-to-be removed features.
    %li
      %code Removed
      for now removed features.
    %li
      %code Fixed
      for any bug fixes.
    %li
      %code Security
      in case of vulnerabilities.

  %h4#which-type.new
    %a.anchor{ href: "#which-type", aria_hidden: "true" }
    Should it go under Changed, Fixed, or Security?

  %p.new
    These three overlap often enough to be worth a rule of thumb:

  %ul.new
    %li
      <strong>Fixed</strong> — behavior that was <em>wrong</em> (it didn't match
      what you documented or intended) now works correctly.
    %li
      <strong>Changed</strong> — behavior that was <em>working as intended</em> now
      works differently; existing users may need to adjust even though nothing was
      broken.
    %li
      <strong>Security</strong> — a fix or change that addresses a
      <em>vulnerability</em>. It could fit under Fixed or Changed, but its audience
      and urgency differ enough to call out on its own.

  %p.new
    When in doubt, ask whether the old behavior was a bug. If it was, it's
    <code>Fixed</code>; if it was intentional and you're changing it, it's
    <code>Changed</code>.

  %h4#more-types.new
    %a.anchor{ href: "#more-types", aria_hidden: "true" }
    Why aren't there more types of changes?

  %p.new
    The six types answer one question: what <em>kind</em> of change is this? That's
    deliberately a small, stable vocabulary — people write these as headings in
    their own changelogs, so fewer and clearer is better.

  %p.new
    Requests for more types usually describe a <em>reason</em>, not a kind. A change
    might be an improvement, an optimization, a refactor, a performance win, or a
    dependency bump — but those belong in the wording of the entry, not in a new
    heading. "Rewrote the JSON parser; about three times faster on large files" says
    more under <code>Changed</code> than a bare <code>Performance</code> heading
    ever could.

  %p.new
    Two common requests deserve a direct answer:

  %ul.new
    %li
      <strong>Dependencies</strong> aren't a kind of change on their own — a bump
      can be harmless, a fix, or breaking. If it's notable to the people using your
      software, describe its <em>effect</em> under the relevant type; if it isn't, it
      doesn't belong here.
    %li
      <strong>Known issues</strong> are discovered, not changed. Note them on the
      affected release or track them in your issue tracker; when one is resolved, it
      lands under <code>Fixed</code>.

  %p.new
    Add a type for every nuance and you're back to categorizing every commit — the
    exact tedium a changelog exists to spare your readers.

  %h4#breaking.new
    %a.anchor{ href: "#breaking", aria_hidden: "true" }
    How do I mark breaking changes?

  %p.new
    If you follow a #{link_to "versioning scheme", data.links.schemes}, the version
    number already hints at this: under #{link_to "Semantic Versioning", data.links.semver}
    a major release like <code>2.0.0</code> is where breaking changes belong. But the
    number alone is easy to overlook, so call them out in the entry itself.

  %p.new
    Breaking changes almost always live under <code>Changed</code> or
    <code>Removed</code>. Rather than adding a separate section for them, prepend a
    short <code>**Breaking:**</code> marker so they stand out while skimming and stay
    grouped with the kind of change they are:

  %p.new <code>- **Breaking:** parse() now returns a result object instead of raising.</code>

  %p.new
    Above all, be explicit about <em>what</em> breaks. "Breaking" only means something
    once readers know which interface you treat as stable — a command line, a library
    API, a wire protocol, a file format, a configuration schema. State which surface
    your versioning scheme covers, and a breaking change becomes unambiguous.

.effort

  %h3#effort
    %a.anchor{ href: "#effort", aria_hidden: "true" }
    How can I reduce the effort required to maintain a changelog?

  %p.updated
    First, start by keeping an <code>Unreleased</code> section at the top of your 
    changelog to track upcoming changes.

  %p This serves two purposes:

  %ul
    %li
      People can see what changes they might expect in upcoming releases
    %li
      At release time, you can move the <code>Unreleased</code> section
      changes into a new release version section.

  %p.new
    Second, consider that communicating about project changes is a critical 
    aspect of maintaining it. Maybe it isn't your preferred focus, but 
    contributors and users hugely benefit from changelogs. 

  %p.new 
    There are many ways you can reduce the maintenance friction of a changelog, 
    but be careful about accidentally making your project tedious to maintain 
    *because* of your changelog. 
  
  %p.new
    %strong 
      Making changes and communicating about changes are two fundamentally 
      different things.
  
  %p.new
    "Don’t let your friends dump git logs into changelogs." doesn't mean "let 
    your enemies turn your changelogs into git commits". The curation process 
    involved in synthesizing <em>notable</em> changes inherently implies that 
    there are non-notable changes to a project which don't belong in a changelog.
    Attempting to categorize these changes when they are being made is not only 
    counter-productive, it's an exercise in tedium I wouldn't wish on anyone. 

.bad-practices
  %h3#bad-practices
    %a.anchor{ href: "#bad-practices", aria_hidden: "true" }
    Can changelogs be bad?

  %p Yes. Here are a few ways they can be less than useful.

  %h4#log-diffs
    %a.anchor{ href: "#log-diffs", aria_hidden: "true" }
    Commit log diffs

  %p
    Using commit log diffs as changelogs is a bad idea: they're full of
    noise. Things like merge commits, commits with obscure titles,
    documentation changes, etc.

  %p
    The purpose of a commit is to document a step in the evolution of
    the source code. Some projects clean up commits, some don't.

  %p
    The purpose of a changelog entry is to document the noteworthy
    difference, often across multiple commits, to communicate them
    clearly to end users.

  %h4#ignoring-deprecations
    %a.anchor{ href: "#ignoring-deprecations", aria_hidden: "true" }
    Ignoring Deprecations

  %p
    When people upgrade from one version to another, it should be
    painfully clear when something will break. It should be possible to
    upgrade to a version that lists deprecations, remove what's
    deprecated, then upgrade to the version where the deprecations
    become removals.

  %p
    If you do nothing else, list deprecations, removals, and any
    breaking changes in your changelog.


  %h4#confusing-dates
    %a.anchor{ href: "#confusing-dates", aria_hidden: "true" }
    Confusing Dates

  %p
    Regional date formats vary throughout the world and it's often
    difficult to find a human-friendly date format that feels intuitive
    to everyone. The advantage of dates formatted like
    <code>2017-07-17</code> is that they follow the order of largest to
    smallest units: year, month, and day. This format also doesn't
    overlap in ambiguous ways with other date formats, unlike some
    regional formats that switch the position of month and day numbers.
    These reasons, and the fact this date format is an
    #{link_to "ISO standard", data.links.isodate}, are why it is the recommended date
    format for changelog entries.

  %h4#inconsistent-changes
    %a.anchor{ href: "#inconsistent-changes", aria_hidden: "true" }
    Inconsistent Changes

  %p.updated
    A changelog which only mentions some of the changes can be as dangerous
    as not having a changelog at all. 
    
  %p.updated
    While many of the changes may not be relevant - for instance, removing a single whitespace may not need
    to be recorded in all instances - any important changes should be
    mentioned in the changelog. By inconsistently applying changes,
    your users may mistakenly think that the changelog is the single source
    of truth. It ought to be. With great power comes great responsibility -
    having a good changelog means having a consistently updated changelog.

  %aside
    There’s more. Help me collect these antipatterns by
    = link_to "opening an issue", data.links.issue
    or a pull request.

.frequently-asked-questions
  %h3#frequently-asked-questions
    %a.anchor{ href: "#frequently-asked-questions", aria_hidden: "true" }
    Frequently Asked Questions

  %h4#standard
    %a.anchor{ href: "#standard", aria_hidden: "true" }
    Is there a standard changelog format?

  %p.updated
    When this project first started, there were of course the 
    #{link_to "GNU changelog style guide", data.links.gnustyle},
    or the #{link_to "two-paragraph-long GNU NEWS file", data.links.gnunews}
    "guideline". But those were in many ways insufficient. Keep a Changelog 
    doesn't aim to be the one true standard for changelogs, but it does aim to 
    show how useful thoughtful communication about iterative changes can be. 

  %p.updated
    This project aims to be a 
    #{link_to "better changelog convention", data.links.changelog}. It started 
    based on observation of good practices in the open source software community
    but it can be useful to any project which sees frequent changes, particularly 
    changes that require outward-facing communication.

  %p.updated
    Open #{link_to "discussions", data.links.discussions} and
    #{link_to "suggestions for improvements", data.links.issue} are welcome.

  %h4#versioning.new
    %a.anchor{ href: "#versioning", aria_hidden: "true" }
    Do I have to use Semantic Versioning?

  %p.new
    No. #{link_to "Semantic Versioning", data.links.semver} is popular and useful,
    especially for libraries, but it isn't the only
    #{link_to "versioning scheme", data.links.schemes}. Many projects use
    #{link_to "calendar versioning", data.links.calver} like <code>2024.06</code>, a
    plain incrementing number, or a date. What matters for a changelog is that you note
    which scheme you use, so readers know how to read your version numbers.

  %p.new
    Some projects don't ship discrete, numbered versions at all — a continuously
    deployed web service, for instance. A changelog still helps: keep an
    <code>Unreleased</code> section for upcoming changes, and record what shipped under
    dated entries even when there's no version number to attach them to.


  %h4#filename
    %a.anchor{ href: "#filename", aria_hidden: "true" }
    What should the changelog file be named?

  %p
    Call it <code>CHANGELOG.md</code>. Some projects use
    <code>HISTORY</code>, <code>NEWS</code> or <code>RELEASES</code>.

  %p
    While it's easy to think that the name of your changelog file
    doesn't matter that much, why make it harder for your end users to
    consistently find notable changes?

  %p.new
    Some may argue that a `CHANGELOG` file should... log all changes that
    occurred. This is absurd on its face given all modern version control tools
    and code hosting platforms offer this output without the need for a static 
    export. Rather than be pedantic about the common usage of the word 
    "changelog", it seems more fruitful to work toward improving them.   

  %h4#releases
    %a.anchor{ href: "#releases", aria_hidden: "true" }
    What about Releases?

  %p.updated
    Code hosting platforms offer ways to publish release posts. Nowadays
    many projects communicate about version releases using these posts. Posts
    can be created from version-specific git tags.

  %p.updated
    The value of these release posts is limited. They often encourage
    maintainers to create information about project changes that is not portable
    across code hosting platforms. When release notes are published exclusively
    in these posts, they're not kept in version history, unlike a changelog
    text file stored in the repository.

  %p.updated
    It's best to focus on changelog text files first and either derive these
    individual release posts manually or use tools to create release posts
    when a new version is added to the changelog.

  %h4#release-notes.new
    %a.anchor{ href: "#release-notes", aria_hidden: "true" }
    Is a changelog the same as release notes?

  %p.new
    They overlap, but they serve different audiences and live in different places. A
    changelog lives in the repository next to the code and records precisely what
    changed between versions, for anyone who needs to know — contributors and users
    alike. Release notes are usually a curated announcement for a single release:
    highlights, upgrade steps, and a bit of marketing.

  %p.new
    A good changelog is an excellent <em>source</em> for release notes. Derive the
    notes from it — keep the notable entries, drop the ones only contributors care
    about, add narrative — instead of maintaining two records by hand. This is also the
    cleaner answer to separating "internal" from "public" changes: curate notable,
    outward-facing changes in the changelog, then generate whatever narrower view an
    audience needs.

  %h4#summary.new
    %a.anchor{ href: "#summary", aria_hidden: "true" }
    Can a release start with a summary?

  %p.new
    Yes. It's perfectly fine to open a version with a short, high-level note —
    placed right under the version heading, before the first <code>### Added</code>
    or <code>### Changed</code> section. A sentence or two is enough to summarize the
    theme of a release, tease a headline feature, or explain the thinking behind a
    significant change.

  %p.new
    Larger, popular projects do this often, and it can make a release much easier to
    take in at a glance. Keep it brief and let the typed sections carry the detail —
    the summary sets context, it doesn't replace the itemized list of notable
    changes.

  %p.new
    It's entirely optional, though. Most releases don't need one, and you shouldn't
    feel obliged to write a summary just to fill space. Reach for one when a release
    has a story worth telling, and skip it when the sections speak for themselves.

  %h4#automatic
    %a.anchor{ href: "#automatic", aria_hidden: "true" }
    Can changelogs be automatically parsed?

  %p.updated
    It’s difficult, because people follow wildly different formats and
    file names. But if a project follows a consistent format (like the one 
    recommended here) it can be very useful. 
    
  %p.new
    For example, it's rare to see people immediately upgrade as soon as a new 
    version is released. By the time they're able to, there may be multiple 
    versions to consider. 
    
  %p.new
    An automatically parsed changelog can help people see a filtered list of
    changes between specific versions, making their upgrade process much easier.

  %p.new
    There's no separate machine format to learn, and there won't be one. This page
    is the whole of it: a changelog that follows a consistent, predictable shape is
    readable by a parser and by an LLM alike — precisely because it was written for
    people first. Keep a Changelog has spread for over a decade without a formal
    grammar, a schema, or a required file format, and bolting one on now would trade
    the simplicity that made it useful for rigor almost nobody asked for.

  %h4#llms.new
    %a.anchor{ href: "#llms", aria_hidden: "true" }
    What about LLM-generated changelogs?

  %p.new
    An LLM can draft a changelog from a diff in seconds, and as a starting point
    that's genuinely useful. The same ease is the risk: it's now trivial to publish
    a fluent, plausible-looking changelog that no human ever read. The old failure
    mode was a missing changelog; increasingly it's a confident one that buries the
    two changes that mattered under forty that didn't.

  %p.new
    So the principle this project started with matters more, not less, the more code
    LLMs write: <strong>machines can draft, but humans curate</strong>. A diff or a
    pile of commits is raw material; a changelog is the considered, human-facing
    summary of what's worth knowing. Judging what's notable, saying it plainly, and
    leaving out the rest is exactly the part a model can't do for you, because it
    depends on who your readers are and what they care about.

  %p.new
    If you do hand the first draft to a tool, give it the same brief you'd give a
    contributor: summarize the notable, outward-facing changes; never paste a git
    log; sort each into one of the six types; put the <em>why</em> in the wording;
    flag anything breaking; and drop the churn no reader will care about. Then read
    what it wrote before anyone else does.

  %p.new
    If your project leans on coding agents, that brief is worth writing down where
    they'll read it — an <code>AGENTS.md</code>, a <code>CLAUDE.md</code>, or
    whatever instructions file your tools pick up. A link to this page and those few
    rules are all an agent needs to keep your changelog the way you would; there's no
    schema to wire up, because the instructions are the interface.

  %h4#conventional-commits.new
    %a.anchor{ href: "#conventional-commits", aria_hidden: "true" }
    How does this relate to Conventional Commits?

  %p.new
    They address different halves of the same problem.
    #{link_to "Conventional Commits", data.links.conventionalcommits} is a convention
    for writing structured <em>commit messages</em>. Tools like
    #{link_to "semantic-release", data.links.semanticrelease}, release-please,
    Changesets, and git-cliff can read those commits to generate a changelog and pick
    the next version automatically.

  %p.new
    Keep a Changelog describes the other end: the human-facing record those tools are
    trying to produce. They're complementary — you can feed Conventional Commits into a
    generator and have it emit something close to this format.

  %p.new
    Just remember that a generated changelog is a <em>draft</em>. Commits are written
    for the people building the software; a changelog is written for the people using
    it. Deciding what's notable and rewriting it for the reader is precisely the work a
    generator can't do — and it's what makes a changelog worth keeping.

  %h4#ci.new
    %a.anchor{ href: "#ci", aria_hidden: "true" }
    How does a changelog fit into CI/CD?

  %p.new
    Continuous integration can take some of the chore out of keeping a changelog, as
    long as it doesn't become the chore. The safe, useful jobs are mechanical: at
    release time, move the <code>Unreleased</code> section into a new dated version;
    check that the file is well-formed; and, if you like, leave a gentle reminder on
    a pull request that a notable change might deserve an entry.

  %p.new
    What CI can't do is judge the part that matters. No pipeline can tell whether an
    entry is notable, written for humans, or worth reading at all — that's the
    curation a changelog exists for, and it stays a human call. So resist turning the
    changelog into a hard gate that blocks every pull request until someone edits it.
    That just trains contributors to paste in a line to make the check pass, which is
    how you end up with a changelog full of noise — the very thing this is meant to
    prevent.

  %p.new
    Keep CI in a supporting role: let it handle the boring mechanics and the
    reminders, and leave the judgment to the people writing for other people.

  %h4#yanked
    %a.anchor{ href: "#yanked", aria_hidden: "true" }
    What about yanked releases?

  %p
    Yanked releases are versions that had to be pulled because of a
    serious bug or security issue. Often these versions don't even
    appear in change logs. They should. This is how you should display
    them:

  %p <code>## [0.0.5] - 2014-12-13 [YANKED]</code>

  %p
    The <code>[YANKED]</code> tag is loud for a reason. It's important
    for people to notice it. Since it's surrounded by brackets it's also
    easier to parse programmatically.

  %h4#linking.new
    %a.anchor{ href: "#linking", aria_hidden: "true" }
    Should I link to issues or pull requests?

  %p.new
    That's up to you, and it's a reasonable thing to do — a link to the issue or
    pull request behind a change can save a curious reader a lot of digging.

  %p.new
    Just go in with eyes open. Links rot: if a project moves to a new host or
    organization, its issue and pull request URLs can start returning 404s. And
    pull or merge request numbers belong to a particular forge, not to your code —
    they don't travel if you migrate. Git tags and commit references, by contrast,
    are canonical to the repository itself and move with it wherever it goes.

  %p.new
    So link when it genuinely helps, prefer prose over a wall of bare
    <code>(#1234)</code> references, and lean on what's portable — a version tag, a
    commit — when you want a pointer that will still resolve years from now.


  %h4#rewrite
    %a.anchor{ href: "#rewrite", aria_hidden: "true" }
    Should you ever rewrite a changelog?

  %p.updated
    There can be good reasons to improve a changelog after a version has been 
    released. For example some projects may forget to add a changelog entry for
    a version, which would have to be retroactively added to the changelog.

  %p.updated
    It's also possible maintainers may discover they forgot to address a
    breaking change in the notes for a released version. Updating the changelog
    would be sensible in these cases. However it might be a good idea to denote 
    the date at which the changelog was updated for a given version. This may
    help people reading the changelog notice the change.

  %h4#large-changelog.new
    %a.anchor{ href: "#large-changelog", aria_hidden: "true" }
    What if my changelog gets too big?

  %p.new
    A single file is usually fine, even a very long one. A changelog you can open
    and search in one place is easy to navigate, and plenty of large, long-lived
    projects keep decades of history in one <code>CHANGELOG.md</code> without
    trouble.

  %p.new
    If a changelog spanning thousands of releases does become unwieldy, it's
    reasonable to split older history into separate files. The risk is
    accessibility: a reader — or a tool — that only finds the main file may never
    discover the archived entries. So if you split, link clearly from the main
    changelog to the archived ones, and back, so nothing becomes a dead end.

  %p.new
    Split along a line that won't move. Archive versions old enough that they're
    unlikely to ever need editing again, and keep the active, recent history in the
    main file. If your archived files still need updating, you've created a
    maintenance hurdle instead of removing one. And resist pruning old entries
    outright — someone, someday, is upgrading from that ancient version.

  %h4#monorepos.new
    %a.anchor{ href: "#monorepos", aria_hidden: "true" }
    What about monorepos?

  %p.new
    It depends on what the repository actually is. The question to ask is whether it
    holds one product or many.

  %p.new
    If the monorepo houses several unrelated projects that merely share a
    repository, treat them as what they are: each gets its own independent
    changelog, versioned and maintained on its own terms. There's nothing to unify.

  %p.new
    If instead the monorepo is a single system that people know by one name — Ruby
    on Rails is the classic example — per-component changelogs are genuinely useful,
    and projects like it have kept them for years. But on their own they aren't
    enough. It isn't realistic to ask someone to traipse through dozens of component
    changelogs to work out what a unified <code>3.0</code> means for them. Even when
    some components aren't used by everyone, there should be a central changelog
    that synthesizes the notable changes at the scope of the whole project, not just
    scattered across its parts.

  %p.new
    Think of the per-component changelogs as the detailed record and the central one
    as the human-facing summary of what a release means for the project as a whole.
    It's the same principle as everywhere else: write for the person trying to
    understand what changed, not for the structure of your codebase.

  %h4#scope.new
    %a.anchor{ href: "#scope", aria_hidden: "true" }
    What won't Keep a Changelog do?

  %p.new
    A convention is as much about what it refuses as what it recommends, and a few
    popular requests are deliberate non-goals:

  %ul.new
    %li
      It won't keep growing the list of change types. Six is enough; the reason for
      a change belongs in its wording, not in a new heading.
    %li
      It won't define a machine format, a schema, or a required file layout. The
      format is this page, in plain language — readable by people, tools, and models
      alike.
    %li
      It won't become a tool, a service, or a runtime you have to install. Keep a
      Changelog is a convention; following it should cost nothing but attention.
    %li
      It won't tie itself to any one host or vendor. A changelog is a plain file in
      your repository, portable to wherever your code lives.

  %p.new
    None of this is set in stone — it's a considered opinion, open to discussion.
    But the bar for adding to a convention this widely used is high: a change has to
    earn its place against a decade of working just fine without it.


  %h4#contribute
    %a.anchor{ href: "#contribute", aria_hidden: "true" }
    How can I contribute?

  %p.updated
    This project doesn't claim to be the only way to communicate about changes. 
    It's merely a carefully considered opinion, with context and hopefully useful 
    examples. It has helped hundreds of thousands of projects improve their 
    release communication process, but it's just as much of a work in progress.

  %p.updated
    In the decade since Keep a Changelog itself was released, release communication
    has improved dramatically, at least in the open source world. This project 
    played a small part but each evolution was the result of discussion and 
    input from the community.

  %p.updated
    So please #{link_to "contribute", data.links.repo} to Keep a Changelog or 
    start a #{link_to "conversation", data.links.discussions} if you need more help.

  %h4#git.new
    %a.anchor{ href: "#git", aria_hidden: "true" }
    What's a "git log"?

  %p.new
    A git log is a command used by the #{link_to "git", data.links.git}
    distributed #{link_to "version control system", data.links.dvcs} to display
    all changes recorded in a given source code repository.

  %p.new
    Git is a tool used by a large and growing share of software projects around 
    the world. Keep a Changelog is mainly focused on communication about 
    software evolution which is why our tag line references "git log" in a
    slightly caustic way. This is because open source maintainers have long had
    the problematic habit of converting "git log" command output into release notes
    for their projects, with little regard for the actual human beings who had
    to try and digest these so-called "changelogs" made up of hundreds of
    individual changes, often written hastily.

.press
  %h3 Conversations
  %p
    I went on #{link_to "The Changelog podcast", data.links.thechangelog}
    to talk about why maintainers and contributors should care about changelogs,
    and also about the motivations behind this project.
